(verb
  :name "alg/is-normal?"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/is-normal? G H) -> #t | #f"
  :summary "Test whether a subgroup H is normal in G (closed under conjugation)."
  :explanation "A subgroup H of G is normal if gHg⁻¹ = H for all g ∈ G. Equivalently, H is normal iff left and right cosets coincide. Normal subgroups are the kernels of homomorphisms and are essential for constructing quotient groups. This verb accepts a group G and a subgroup H and returns #t if H is normal, #f otherwise. Normality is a gateway to quotient structures."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(let* ((S3 (alg/symmetric 3))\n       (H (list 0 1)))\n  (alg/is-normal? S3 H))" :note "A 2-element subgroup of S₃; not normal because conjugation by transpositions moves it; returns #f")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((G (alg/dihedral 4))\n       (rot (list 0 1 2 3)))\n  (if (alg/is-normal? G rot)\n      'normal\n      'not-normal))" :note "The rotation subgroup of D₄ is normal; returns 'normal")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((G (alg/symmetric 4))\n       (center (alg/center G))\n       (check (alg/is-normal? G center)))\n  (list 'center center 'is-normal? check))" :note "The center is always normal; verifies this for S₄")
  )
  :caveats ("H must be a valid subgroup of G; behavior is undefined if H fails alg/subgroup?." "The verb assumes H is given as an explicit list or set; it does not generate H from generators." "For large |G|, conjugacy computation is expensive; use alg/center or alg/conjugacy-classes for structural shortcuts.")
  :drawbacks ("Exhaustive verification is O(|G|·|H|·log|H|); slow for |G|, |H| > 100." "No algebraic speedup: must verify all conjugates in the worst case.")
  :usecases ("Finding normal subgroups to construct quotient groups." "Verifying that the center (alg/center) or commutator subgroup is normal (they always are)." "Composition series in finite group theory: identifying normal subgroups to build the series.")
  :related ("alg/subgroup?" "alg/center" "alg/conjugacy-classes" "alg/cosets" "alg/index")
  :learn (:concept "A subgroup H is normal iff gHg⁻¹ = H for all g (i.e., conjugation leaves H invariant). Normal subgroups are kernels of homomorphisms." :prerequisites ("alg/subgroup?" "alg/op" "alg/inverse") :progression "After understanding normality, study alg/cosets and quotient group constructions (G/H) using alg/direct-product and composition series.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "Before constructing a quotient G/H, the operator must certify that H is normal — otherwise the coset multiplication is ill-defined and downstream code corrupts."
     :program "(define G (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define A3 (filter (lambda (p) (even? (alg/perm-parity p))) (alg/op G)))\n(alg/is-normal? G A3)"
     :explanation "A_3 has index 2 in S_3; every index-2 subgroup is normal; operator sees #t."
     :meta "subgroup? tests closure; is-normal? adds the conjugation-invariance requirement. Skipping the second test means the 'quotient' is not a group at all.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: group; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'invariance under inner action'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define G (alg/symmetric 3))")
       (:domain "layer respected by all effects" :code "(fx/preserves-layer? layer)")
       (:domain "normal subgroup" :code "gHg^-1 = H ∀ g"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/is-normal? in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''invariance under inner action'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''invariance under inner action'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/is-normal?."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "H ⊴ G iff every left coset equals the corresponding right coset."
     :program "(define G (alg/dihedral 4))\n(define rots (alg/subgroup-gen G (list 1)))\n(alg/is-normal? G rots)"
     :invariant "H ⊴ G ⇔ ∀ g ∈ G. gH = Hg"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the group category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "alg/is-normal? — see :summary."
     :composition "(define G (alg/dihedral 4))\n(define candidates (list (list 0) (alg/subgroup-gen G (list 1))))\n(map (lambda (H) (list H (alg/is-normal? G H))) candidates)"
     :emergent "quotient-eligible"
     :meta "The emergent quotient-eligible belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Normality is the gate for quotient constructions; the same pattern as choosing a 'stable' equivalence class before quotienting.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the group operations close into the quotient-eligible pattern."
     :cs "The emergent quotient-eligible is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/kernel"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/kernel G H φ) -> list (elements g : φ(g) = e_H)"
  :summary "Compute the kernel of a homomorphism φ: the set of all g ∈ G where φ(g) = e_H."
  :explanation "The kernel of a homomorphism φ: G → H is the preimage of the identity: ker(φ) = {g ∈ G : φ(g) = eH}. It is always a normal subgroup of G and measures how far φ is from being injective (one-to-one). The First Isomorphism Theorem states G / ker(φ) ≅ im(φ). This verb accepts two groups and a homomorphism φ and returns the kernel as a list. Understanding kernels is crucial for understanding quotients."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(let* ((Z4 (alg/zn 4))\n       (Z2 (alg/zn 2))\n       (φ (lambda (x) (modulo x 2))))\n  (alg/kernel Z4 Z2 φ))" :note "φ: x ↦ x mod 2 has kernel {0, 2}; returns (0 2)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((S3 (alg/symmetric 3))\n       (Z2 (alg/zn 2))\n       (det (lambda (perm) (alg/perm-sign perm))))\n  (define ker (alg/kernel S3 Z2 det))\n  (list 'kernel ker 'size (length ker)))" :note "The determinant (sign) map S₃ → {±1} has kernel A₃ (alternating group); returns kernel with size 3")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((G (alg/zn 12))\n       (H (alg/zn 4))\n       (φ (lambda (x) (modulo x 4)))\n       (ker (alg/kernel G H φ))\n       (quotient-order (/ (alg/order G) (length ker))))\n  (list 'kernel ker 'quotient-order quotient-order))" :note "By the First Isomorphism Theorem, |G/ker| = |im(φ)|; verifies orders")
  )
  :caveats ("φ must be a valid homomorphism (test with alg/is-homomorphism? beforehand)." "The kernel is always a normal subgroup; the verb does not explicitly mark it as such." "For large |G|, kernel computation is expensive (O(|G|·|H|)).")
  :drawbacks ("Does not return a quotient object; to work with G/ker, manually construct a homomorphic image or use alg/image." "No caching; repeated kernel calls recompute from scratch.")
  :usecases ("Finding the kernel to apply the First Isomorphism Theorem and compute quotient structures." "Analyzing injectivity: if ker(φ) = {e}, then φ is injective." "Constructing normal subgroups from homomorphisms.")
  :related ("alg/is-homomorphism?" "alg/image" "alg/is-normal?" "alg/cosets" "alg/op")
  :learn (:concept "The kernel ker(φ) = {g : φ(g) = e} is a normal subgroup; φ is injective iff ker(φ) = {e}. The First Isomorphism Theorem: G/ker(φ) ≅ im(φ)." :prerequisites ("alg/is-homomorphism?" "alg/identity" "alg/is-normal?") :progression "After computing kernels, explore alg/image and use both together to understand quotient groups and the First Isomorphism Theorem.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A homomorphism's kernel is where the map collapses information; the operator needs to enumerate the collapsed elements before quotienting."
     :program "(define G (alg/zn 6))\n(define H (alg/zn 2))\n(define phi (lambda (x) (modulo x 2)))\n(alg/kernel G H phi)"
     :explanation "Even elements {0, 2, 4} map to 0; operator sees (0 2 4)."
     :meta "Image is what's hit; kernel is what's collapsed. Confusing them leads to backwards conclusions about injectivity.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: group; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'preimage of the identity'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define G (alg/zn 6))")
       (:domain "inputs that produce no state change" :code "(input/no-op-inputs state)")
       (:domain "kernel of a homomorphism" :code "ker(φ) = {g : φ(g) = e_H}"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/kernel in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''preimage of the identity'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''preimage of the identity'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/kernel."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "ker(φ) is a normal subgroup of G."
     :program "(define G (alg/zn 6))\n(define H (alg/zn 3))\n(define phi (lambda (x) (modulo x 3)))\n(alg/is-normal? G (alg/kernel G H phi))"
     :invariant "ker(φ) ⊴ G"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the group category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/kernel — see :summary."
     :composition "(define G (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define Z2 (alg/zn 2))\n(define sgn (lambda (p) (if (even? (alg/perm-parity p)) 0 1)))\n(define A3 (alg/kernel G Z2 sgn))\n(list (length A3) (alg/is-normal? G A3))"
     :emergent "normal-subgroup-from-hom"
     :meta "The emergent normal-subgroup-from-hom belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Kernel-of-hom = normal subgroup; every normal subgroup arises as a kernel.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the group operations close into the normal-subgroup-from-hom pattern."
     :cs "The emergent normal-subgroup-from-hom is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/normal-form"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/normal-form pcs) -> list (the Rahn normal form)"
  :summary "Compute the Rahn normal form of a pitch-class set: the most compact rotation."
  :explanation "In music theory, a pitch-class set (pcs) is a collection of pitch classes mod 12, often written as an unordered set {0, 4, 7} for a major triad. The Rahn normal form is a canonical choice among all rotations and inversions of a pcs: it is the rotation whose interval vector (differences between consecutive elements) is lexicographically smallest when read forward. This ensures unique representation for comparison and analysis. This verb accepts a pcs and returns its Rahn normal form. The normal form is a foundation for pitch-class set analysis."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(alg/normal-form '(0 4 7))" :note "Major triad {C, E, G}; already in normal form; returns (0 4 7)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((pcs1 '(0 1 6))\n       (pcs2 '(1 6 0)))\n  (equal? (alg/normal-form pcs1)\n          (alg/normal-form pcs2)))" :note "Two rotations of the same pcs; both normalize to the same form; returns #t")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pcs '(0 2 5 7))\n       (nf (alg/normal-form pcs))\n       (iv (alg/interval-vector nf)))\n  (list 'set pcs 'normal-form nf 'interval-vector iv))" :note "Computes normal form and then its interval vector for further analysis")
  )
  :caveats ("Input pcs must be a list of integers 0–11 (mod 12 pitch classes); behavior undefined for out-of-range values." "The normal form is *one* choice among several canonical forms (Forte prime form, Babbitt normal form); ensure you match your reference." "Duplicate pitch classes in the input may be silently removed or cause errors; normalize input first.")
  :drawbacks ("Definition varies by music theory text; some include inversion, some don't. Verify against your source." "For large pcs (|pcs| > 6), the number of rotations grows; computation is still fast but not negligible." "Does not return the inversion or other transformations; use alg/invert separately if needed.")
  :usecases ("Canonicalizing pitch-class sets for comparison and database lookup." "Music analysis: identifying equivalent chords across octaves and transpositions." "Composing with fixed pitch-class sets while exploring different orderings (melodic arrangements).")
  :related ("alg/pcset" "alg/prime-form" "alg/interval-vector" "alg/transpose" "alg/invert")
  :learn (:concept "The Rahn normal form is the lexicographically smallest rotation of a pcs's interval vector; it is a canonical representative for unordered pitch sets." :prerequisites ("alg/pcset" "alg/interval-vector") :progression "After mastering normal form, explore alg/prime-form (Forte prime form) and the Neo-Riemannian transforms (alg/nr-P, alg/nr-L, alg/nr-R) for advanced harmonic analysis.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "Two rotations of the same pcset need a canonical representative so they compare equal after normalization."
     :program "(equal? (alg/normal-form (list 4 7 0)) (alg/normal-form (list 0 4 7)))"
     :explanation "Both rotations normalize to the same canonical form; operator sees #t."
     :meta "prime-form goes further and identifies under inversion too; normal-form is one step behind (rotation only).")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: pcset; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'canonical representative under an equivalence'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(equal? (alg/normal-form (list 4 7 0)) (alg/normal-form (list 0 4 7)))")
       (:domain "Unicode NFC normalization" :code "(unicode/nfc s)")
       (:domain "canonical form under cyclic rotation" :code "rotation-canonical(S)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/normal-form in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''canonical representative under an equivalence'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''canonical representative under an equivalence'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/normal-form."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Normal form is idempotent: normalizing a normal form returns it unchanged."
     :program "(define S (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7)))\n(equal? (alg/normal-form S) (alg/normal-form (alg/normal-form S)))"
     :invariant "∀ S. nf(nf(S)) = nf(S)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the pcset category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/normal-form — see :summary."
     :composition "(define rotations (map (lambda (k) (alg/transpose (alg/pcset (list 0 1 4)) k)) (list 0 3 6)))\n(map alg/normal-form rotations)"
     :emergent "rotation-canonical"
     :meta "The emergent rotation-canonical belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Canonicalization = idempotent normalization; same shape as path canonicalization in filesystems. See book-of-composition ch-13.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the pcset operations close into the rotation-canonical pattern."
     :cs "The emergent rotation-canonical is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/nr-L"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/nr-L chord) -> chord"
  :summary "Apply the Neo-Riemannian Leading-tone transform to a triad, swapping the note that moves by semitone."
  :explanation "The Neo-Riemannian L-transform is a music-theoretic operation on pitch-class sets (triads). It keeps two notes fixed and moves the third by one semitone to create a new triad. Geometrically, it represents a reflection across a pitch-class axis; algebraically, it encodes a specific group action on the space of triads. This is one of three fundamental PLR transforms used in chromatic harmony analysis."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define C-major (list 0 4 7))\n(alg/nr-L C-major)" :note "L-transform moves the root C to B, giving a new triad; see the result")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define chord (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7)))\n(define l-image (alg/nr-L chord))\n(alg/nr-L l-image)" :note "Applying L twice from a normalized pcset shows the double-transform; traces the orbit")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define explore-plr\n  (let ((start (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7))))\n    (let ((l (alg/nr-L start))\n          (p (alg/nr-P start))\n          (r (alg/nr-R start)))\n      (list start l p r))))\nexplore-plr" :note "Compare all three NR-transforms from one triad; shows the group structure")
  )
  :caveats ("Input should be a valid pitch-class set (list of integers 0–11) or a triad; non-triadic inputs may produce unexpected results" "The L-transform is an involution (L∘L = identity) in the usual PL-group action" "Results are mod 12 (pitch-class arithmetic)")
  :drawbacks ("Only sensible for triadic harmony; larger or smaller pc-sets require different tools" "Does not preserve all voice-leading properties; for optimization over voice-leading distance, consider `alg/orbit` with a custom action")
  :usecases ("Analyzing chromatic progressions in Romantic and post-tonal music" "Generating triad sequences by composing L, P, and R transforms" "Exploring the structure of the Tonnetz (neo-Riemannian pitch-class space)")
  :related ("alg/nr-P" "alg/nr-R" "alg/pcset" "alg/triad" "alg/op" "alg/orbit")
  :learn (:concept "group actions on pitch-class sets; neo-Riemannian transformations as reflections and involutions" :prerequisites ("alg/pcset" "alg/triad") :progression "Understand all three NR-transforms (L, P, R), then explore `alg/orbit` to see what chord sequences they generate")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A late-Romantic harmonic analysis needs to trace an L-transform sequence; the audit wants a single call that returns the transformed triad rather than trigonometry over voicings."
     :program "(alg/nr-L (alg/triad 0 'major))"
     :explanation "C major L→ E minor; operator sees the transformed triad."
     :meta "P swaps parallel major/minor at the same root; L swaps at the leading-tone. Different musical effects, same group family.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: pcset; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'reflection in a chord space'"
