(verb
  :name "alg/nr-R"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/nr-R chord) -> chord"
  :summary "Apply the Neo-Riemannian Relative transform to a triad, swapping major ↔ minor with the related root."
  :explanation "The R-transform relates a major triad to its relative minor (e.g., C major ↔ A minor), or a minor to its relative major. The new root is either a third above (major→minor) or a third below (minor→major). It shares two pitch classes with the original triad and moves the third by two semitones. R is the most 'distant' of the three NR-transforms in voice-leading cost but generates musically important harmonic relationships."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define C-major (list 0 4 7))\n(alg/nr-R C-major)" :note "C major becomes A minor; shares pitch classes C and E, moves G to A")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define minor (alg/triad 9 'minor))\n(define major (alg/nr-R minor))\nmajor" :note "A minor (9 0 4) becomes C major (0 4 7); R is also an involution")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define plr-cycle\n  (let loop ((chord (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7)))\n             (moves (list))\n             (count 0))\n    (if (= count 12)\n      (reverse moves)\n      (let ((r-chord (alg/nr-R chord)))\n        (loop r-chord (cons chord moves) (+ count 1))))))\nplr-cycle" :note "Repeated R-transforms from a single triad; traces a cycle through major/minor space")
  )
  :caveats ("R swaps to the *relative* key, not the parallel; root changes significantly" "Two of the three pitch classes are preserved; one moves by two semitones (a major/minor third)" "Results are mod 12; the returned chord is guaranteed valid if input is a valid triad")
  :drawbacks ("R introduces the largest voice-leading distance among PLR; may not be ideal for smooth progressions" "For harmonic generation, R alone does not close quickly (the cycle is long)")
  :usecases ("Analyzing relative major/minor relationships in tonal music" "Generating chord sequences that explore tonal ambiguity" "Understanding the Tonnetz structure in three dimensions")
  :related ("alg/nr-L" "alg/nr-P" "alg/pcset" "alg/triad" "alg/op" "alg/orbit")
  :learn (:concept "relative major/minor; neo-Riemannian group; pitch-class transformations as symmetries" :prerequisites ("alg/pcset" "alg/triad") :progression "Study all three NR-transforms, then use `alg/orbit` to understand the structure of sequences generated by composing them")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "Relative major/minor moves in Romantic music are R-transforms; the analysis needs to trace them mechanically."
     :program "(alg/nr-R (alg/triad 0 'major))"
     :explanation "C major R→ A minor; operator sees (9 0 4) or the sorted (0 4 9)."
     :meta "L moves one note by semitone; R moves one note by whole-step. R travels further in voice-leading space.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: pcset; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'reflection to relative key'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(alg/nr-R (alg/triad 0 'major))")
       (:domain "scene key-signature change" :code "(scene/relative-key-shift stage)")
       (:domain "R-involution" :code "R: T → T"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/nr-R in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''reflection to relative key'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''reflection to relative key'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/nr-R."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "R is an involution: R∘R = identity."
     :program "(define c (alg/triad 0 'major))\n(equal? c (alg/nr-R (alg/nr-R c)))"
     :invariant "∀ triad t. R(R(t)) = t"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the pcset category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/nr-R — see :summary."
     :composition "(define c (alg/triad 0 'major))\n(define cycle (let loop ((n 0) (cur c) (acc '()))\n  (cond ((= n 6) (reverse acc))\n        (else (loop (+ n 1) (alg/nr-R (alg/nr-L cur)) (cons cur acc))))))\ncycle"
     :emergent "hexatonic-cycle"
     :meta "The emergent hexatonic-cycle belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. RL alternation generates hexatonic cycles — a foundational neo-Riemannian pattern.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the pcset operations close into the hexatonic-cycle pattern."
     :cs "The emergent hexatonic-cycle is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/op"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/op G a b) -> c"
  :summary "Compute the product a·b in a group G, where G is a group structure (Cayley table, permutation group, or algebraic group)."
  :explanation "The group operation `alg/op` is the fundamental binary operation that defines a group. It takes a group structure G (typically represented as a Cayley multiplication table or implicitly via a group presentation) and two elements a, b, and returns their product a·b according to the group's binary operation. The result must be associative, have an identity, and every element must have an inverse (properties checked by `alg/is-group?`)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define G (alg/cyclic 5))\n(alg/op G 2 3)" :note "In the cyclic group Z/5Z, 2+3=5≡0 mod 5; result is 0")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define S3 (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define a (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define b (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(alg/op S3 a b)" :note "Compose two permutations in the symmetric group S₃; result is a permutation")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define G 'G)\n(define traverse-subgroup\n  (let loop ((elt (alg/identity G))\n             (gen (list 0 1))\n             (result (list)))\n    (if (>= (length result) (alg/order G))\n      result\n      (let ((next (alg/op G elt (car gen))))\n        (loop next (cdr gen) (cons elt result))))))\ntraverse-subgroup" :note "Walk through a group by repeated operation with a generator; builds a subgroup orbit")
  )
  :caveats ("The group G must be a valid group structure (checked with `alg/is-group?`)" "Elements a and b must be valid members of G; out-of-range or malformed elements produce 'nan or error" "The operation is not necessarily commutative (a·b ≠ b·a in non-abelian groups)" "Order matters: `alg/op G a b` ≠ `alg/op G b a` in general")
  :drawbacks ("For very large groups, multiplication tables consume memory; permutation representation or lazy evaluation may be faster" "No automatic simplification (e.g., if result is identity, it is still returned as-is, not as a canonical representation)")
  :usecases ("Building sequences of group elements by iteration (e.g., a, a², a³, …)" "Testing group axioms (closure, associativity) in computational algebra" "Composing symmetries in geometric applications")
  :related ("alg/identity" "alg/inverse" "alg/element-order" "alg/is-abelian?" "alg/is-group?" "alg/cyclic" "alg/symmetric" "alg/perm-compose")
  :learn (:concept "group operation as the fundamental binary structure; closure and composition" :prerequisites ("alg/identity" "alg/is-group?") :progression "Master `alg/op`, then explore `alg/element-order`, `alg/subgroup-gen`, and group homomorphisms")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "An algebra script needs the group's binary operation as a first-class function to fold over lists of elements — no built-in fold works without the operation."
     :program "(define G (alg/cyclic 5))\n(define product (foldl (lambda (x acc) (alg/op G x acc)) (alg/identity G) (list 1 2 3 4)))\nproduct"
     :explanation "Fold multiplies 1·2·3·4 in Z/5Z; 1+2+3+4=10≡0 mod 5; operator sees 0."
     :meta "alg/orbit does a group action, not a pairwise op; the audit needs pairwise composition, and alg/op is the direct primitive.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: group; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'binary composition inside a closed set'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define G (alg/cyclic 5))")
       (:domain "two sprites overlaid into one" :code "(sprite/overlay a b)")
       (:domain "group operation G × G → G" :code "(g, h) ↦ g·h"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/op in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''binary composition inside a closed set'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''binary composition inside a closed set'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/op."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "alg/op is associative, has identity, and is closed on G."
     :program "(define G (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define perms (alg/op G))\n(define a (car perms)) (define b (cadr perms)) (define c (caddr perms))\n(equal? (alg/op G a (alg/op G b c))\n        (alg/op G (alg/op G a b) c))"
     :invariant "∀ a b c ∈ G. (a·b)·c = a·(b·c)  ∧  a·b ∈ G"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the group category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "alg/op — see :summary."
     :composition "(define G (alg/dihedral 3))\n(define e (alg/identity G))\n(define g 1)\n(let loop ((n 0) (cur e) (acc '()))\n  (cond ((= n 3) (reverse acc))\n        (else (loop (+ n 1) (alg/op G cur g) (cons cur acc)))))"
     :emergent "power-sequence"
     :meta "The emergent power-sequence belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. op + identity + iterate = power sequence; the same as repeated squaring in modular arithmetic. See book-of-code ch-11 (the-alu).")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the group operations close into the power-sequence pattern."
     :cs "The emergent power-sequence is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/orbit"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/orbit G x act) -> (list ...)"
  :summary "Compute the orbit of a point x under the action of a group G, where the action is defined by a function act."
  :explanation "An orbit is the set of all images of a point x under all elements of a group G, under a specified action. The action is a function `(act g x)` that applies group element g to point x. The orbit is the closure of x under repeated application of the group: {g·x : g ∈ G}. Orbits partition the set on which G acts; points in the same orbit are equivalent under the group's symmetry."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define G (alg/cyclic 4))\n(define act (lambda (g x) (modulo (+ x g) 4)))\n(alg/orbit G 0 act)" :note "Orbit of 0 under cyclic addition mod 4; result is (0 1 2 3)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define D3 (alg/dihedral 3))\n(define act (lambda (g p) (alg/apply-symmetry g p)))\n(define pt (list 1 0))\n(alg/orbit D3 pt act)" :note "Orbit of a point under the dihedral group (rotations and reflections of a triangle)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define count-orbits\n  (let ((G (alg/symmetric 4)))\n    (let loop ((points (list 0 1 2 3))\n               (seen (list))\n               (orbits (list)))\n      (if (null? points)\n        orbits\n        (let ((x (car points)))\n          (if (member x seen)\n            (loop (cdr points) seen orbits)\n            (let ((orb (alg/orbit G x (lambda (g p) (alg/perm-apply g p)))))\n              (loop (cdr points) (append seen orb) (cons orb orbits)))))))))\ncount-orbits" :note "Partition a set into orbits under a permutation group; shows orbit-stabilizer structure")
  )
  :caveats ("The action function must be well-defined for all g ∈ G and all x; ill-defined actions produce 'nan or error" "Orbits are unordered sets returned as lists; may contain duplicates if the action is degenerate" "For large groups or continuous actions, orbit computation may be slow or infinite")
  :drawbacks ("No automatic cycle detection for infinite groups; use a finite subgroup or bounded iteration" "The act function is user-provided, so correctness is not guaranteed by the interpreter")
  :usecases ("Partitioning a set by group action (e.g., coloring a graph modulo rotations)" "Understanding the structure of Burnside's lemma and Pólya enumeration" "Computing equivalence classes under symmetry")
  :related ("alg/stabilizer" "alg/op" "alg/is-group?" "alg/apply-symmetry" "alg/cyclic" "alg/dihedral" "alg/symmetric")
  :learn (:concept "group actions and orbits; equivalence under symmetry; orbit-stabilizer theorem" :prerequisites ("alg/op" "alg/is-group?") :progression "Compute orbits, then explore `alg/stabilizer` to understand the orbit-stabilizer theorem")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A tile-decoration script computes all rotations and reflections of a base tile position; the operator wants a single call that returns the orbit rather than looping in user code."
     :program "(define D4 (alg/dihedral 4))\n(define act (lambda (g p) (alg/apply-symmetry g p)))\n(alg/orbit D4 (list 1 0) act)"
     :explanation "Orbit of (1,0) under D_4 has 4 distinct positions (the 4 cardinal directions); operator sees a 4-element list."
     :meta "subgroup-gen closes a subset under the group operation; orbit acts an external group on a point outside the group. Different but often confused.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: group; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'closure of a point under group action'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define D4 (alg/dihedral 4))")
       (:domain "all mirrored copies of a sprite" :code "(sprite/all-symmetric-copies sp)")
       (:domain "orbit of a group action" :code "G·x = {g·x : g ∈ G}"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/orbit in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''closure of a point under group action'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''closure of a point under group action'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/orbit."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
