(verb
  :name "alg/order"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/order G) -> n"
  :summary "Return the order (cardinality) of a group G, i.e., the number of elements |G|."
  :explanation "The order of a group is simply the count of distinct elements it contains. For finite groups, this is a key invariant that constrains the structure; by Lagrange's theorem, the order of any subgroup divides the order of the group. The order of a group is fundamental to understanding its properties (e.g., all groups of order p for prime p are cyclic)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define G (alg/cyclic 7))\n(alg/order G)" :note "The cyclic group Z/7Z has order 7")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define D4 (alg/dihedral 4))\n(define H (alg/subgroup-gen D4 (list 0 1)))\n(alg/order H)" :note "The dihedral group D₄ (symmetries of a square) has order 8; its subgroup may be smaller")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define lagrange-check\n  (let ((G (alg/symmetric 4)))\n    (let ((order-G (alg/order G)))\n      (let loop ((subgroups (list))\n                 (H-list (list)))\n        (let ((divides-check\n               (map (lambda (h)\n                      (= (modulo order-G (alg/order h)) 0))\n                    H-list)))\n          divides-check)))))\nlagrange-check" :note "Verify Lagrange's theorem: every subgroup order divides the group order")
  )
  :caveats ("The order is always a positive integer for finite groups" "For infinite groups, `alg/order` may return a sentinel value or error; use only on finite groups" "The group G must be valid; malformed groups return 'nan or error")
  :drawbacks ("For very large groups, computing the order may be expensive; no memoization by default")
  :usecases ("Checking divisibility constraints (Lagrange's theorem) on subgroups" "Classifying groups by order (e.g., all groups of order 4 are either Z/4Z or Klein four-group)" "Verifying that a constructed group has the expected size")
  :related ("alg/element-order" "alg/is-group?" "alg/cyclic" "alg/dihedral" "alg/symmetric" "alg/subgroup?" "alg/index")
  :learn (:concept "group order as a fundamental invariant; Lagrange's theorem" :prerequisites ("alg/is-group?") :progression "Understand group order, then explore subgroup orders and indices via `alg/index`")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A verification pass needs to check that a group construction produced the intended cardinality — a mismatch is a bug in either the construction or the caller's understanding."
     :program "(define G (alg/dihedral 5))\n(= (alg/order G) 10)"
     :explanation "D_5 must have 10 elements; the operator gets #t confirming the construction is correct."
     :meta "alg/element-order asks about a single element; alg/order asks about the whole group. Confusing them silently gives wrong subgroup-index calculations.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: group; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'cardinality of a finite algebraic object'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define G (alg/dihedral 5))")
       (:domain "sprite count in a scene" :code "(scene/sprite-count stage)")
       (:domain "|G| — the size of a finite set" :code "|X|"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/order in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''cardinality of a finite algebraic object'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''cardinality of a finite algebraic object'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/order."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "For any subgroup H ≤ G, |H| divides |G| (Lagrange)."
     :program "(define G (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define H (alg/subgroup-gen G (list (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))))\n(zero? (modulo (alg/order G) (length H)))"
     :invariant "∀ H ≤ G. |H| | |G|"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the group category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "alg/order — see :summary."
     :composition "(define G (alg/dihedral 4))\n(map (lambda (H) (list (length H) (/ (alg/order G) (length H))))\n     (map (lambda (g) (alg/subgroup-gen G (list g))) (alg/op G)))"
     :emergent "subgroup-lattice"
     :meta "The emergent subgroup-lattice belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. The lattice of subgroups indexed by order is a classical structural fingerprint.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the group operations close into the subgroup-lattice pattern."
     :cs "The emergent subgroup-lattice is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/pcset"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/pcset notes) -> pcset"
  :summary "Normalize a list of notes (pitch classes) to a canonical pitch-class set, sorted and reduced modulo 12."
  :explanation "A pitch-class set (pcset) is a collection of pitch classes (integers 0–11, representing the 12 semitones of an octave), unordered and without duplicates. `alg/pcset` takes any list of integers and returns a canonical form: duplicates removed, values reduced mod 12, and sorted in ascending order. This enables consistent comparison and analysis of harmonic structures independent of octave and transposition."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define notes (list 0 4 7 12 16))\n(alg/pcset notes)" :note "Reduces mod 12: 12→0, 16→4; removes duplicate 0 and 4; result is (0 4 7)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define c-major-octaves (list 0 4 7 12 16 19))\n(define e-minor-octaves (list 4 7 12 15 19))\n(equal? (alg/pcset c-major-octaves) (alg/pcset e-minor-octaves))" :note "Different octaves and transpositions; both normalize to triadic pcsets; checks equality")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define invert-and-normalize\n  (let ((original (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7))))\n    (let ((inverted (alg/invert original 0)))\n      (let ((transposed (alg/transpose inverted 5)))\n        (alg/pcset transposed)))))\ninvert-and-normalize" :note "Chain transformations: invert, transpose, then normalize; shows composition")
  )
  :caveats ("Input notes outside 0–11 are reduced modulo 12; negative notes are also reduced (e.g., -1 → 11)" "Duplicates are silently removed; no warning if the input had them" "The result is always a sorted list of unique integers in [0, 12)")
  :drawbacks ("Loses information about octave register; use for harmonic analysis, not voice-leading" "No preservation of input order; for ordered sets, use a different representation")
  :usecases ("Normalizing chords for comparison and analysis" "Preparing pitch data for neo-Riemannian transformations (L, P, R)" "Identifying pitch-class equivalence across octaves and transpositions")
  :related ("alg/transpose" "alg/invert" "alg/normal-form" "alg/prime-form" "alg/triad" "alg/nr-L" "alg/nr-P" "alg/nr-R")
  :learn (:concept "pitch-class sets as unordered, octave-invariant harmonic objects; canonical forms in music analysis" :prerequisites () :progression "Normalize a pcset, then explore transformations like transpose and invert; then study normal forms")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A composer needs to canonicalize a chord written as C, E, G into the pitch-class set {0, 4, 7} for further algebraic analysis."
     :program "(alg/pcset (list 12 16 19))"
     :explanation "Pitches mod 12 → {0, 4, 7}; operator sees the sorted set."
     :meta "normal-form picks a canonical rotation; pcset just reduces mod 12 and dedupes. Use pcset first, then normal-form to compare across rotations.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: pcset; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'reduction to canonical residues'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(alg/pcset (list 12 16 19))")
       (:domain "hash-key normalization" :code "(hash/canon key)")
       (:domain "mod-12 quotient" :code "Z → Z/12Z"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/pcset in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''reduction to canonical residues'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''reduction to canonical residues'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/pcset."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Every pitch-class set is a subset of Z/12Z; pcset returns the sorted deduped mod-12 residues."
     :program "(equal? (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7 12 16)) (alg/pcset (list 0 4 7)))"
     :invariant "pcset(L) = sort(dedupe({x mod 12 : x ∈ L}))"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the pcset category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "alg/pcset — see :summary."
     :composition "(define chord (alg/pcset (list 60 64 67)))\n(alg/interval-vector chord)"
     :emergent "harmonic-fingerprint"
     :meta "The emergent harmonic-fingerprint belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Pcset + interval-vector is the standard set-class fingerprint in music theory.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the pcset operations close into the harmonic-fingerprint pattern."
     :cs "The emergent harmonic-fingerprint is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm image-vec) -> perm"
  :summary "Construct a permutation from a 0-based image vector; returns 'nan if the input is not a valid permutation."
  :explanation "A permutation is a bijection from a finite set to itself. It is represented as a vector [π(0), π(1), …, π(n-1)] where π maps index i to value π(i). For the image vector to be a valid permutation, it must be a rearrangement of [0, 1, …, n-1] with no repeats and no missing values. `alg/perm` validates and stores the permutation; if invalid, it returns 'nan."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define swap-01 (alg/perm (list 1 0 2 3)))\nswap-01" :note "Creates a permutation that swaps indices 0 and 1, leaving 2 and 3 fixed")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define p1 (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define p2 (alg/perm (list 2 1 0)))\n(define prod (alg/perm-compose p1 p2))\nprod" :note "Compose two permutations; result is also a permutation (bijection)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define find-all-degree-3\n  (let loop ((images (list))\n             (gen (list)))\n    (if (null? images)\n      gen\n      (let ((image (car images)))\n        (let ((p (alg/perm image)))\n          (if (equal? p 'nan)\n            (loop (cdr images) gen)\n            (loop (cdr images) (cons p gen))))))))\nfind-all-degree-3" :note "Filters valid degree-3 permutations from a list of candidates")
  )
  :caveats ("Input must be a list of integers; non-integer or out-of-range values cause validation failure → 'nan" "Duplicates in the input invalidate the permutation; all elements must be distinct" "Missing indices invalidate the permutation; the image must include all of {0, …, n-1}" "The atom 'nan is returned on failure; use `equal?` to test for validity")
  :drawbacks ("No automatic degree inference; degree is implicit in the image length" "Error messages are minimal; use custom validation if detailed diagnostics are needed")
  :usecases ("Building permutations by hand for testing and analysis" "Validating user input before composition or inversion" "Generating permutation groups by composition of validated elements")
  :related ("alg/perm-compose" "alg/perm-apply" "alg/perm-inverse" "alg/perm-identity" "alg/perm->cycles" "alg/cycles->perm" "alg/symmetric")
  :learn (:concept "permutations as bijections; array representation and validation" :prerequisites () :progression "Build a permutation, apply it with `alg/perm-apply`, compose with `alg/perm-compose`, and explore cycle notation")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A puzzle solver needs a concrete permutation object from an array — the array-form is what humans read and what test cases store."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 2 0 1 3)))\n(alg/perm-apply p 0)"
     :explanation "Array [2 0 1 3] sends 0 → 2; operator sees 2."
     :meta "cycles->perm accepts cycle-notation; alg/perm accepts array-notation. Both are valid inputs; alg/perm is the more direct answer when the array is what you have.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'total function from finite set to itself'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 2 0 1 3)))")
       (:domain "sprite index remapping" :code "(sprite/remap-indices arr)")
       (:domain "bijection on {0,...,n-1}" :code "π: {0,...,n-1} → {0,...,n-1}"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''total function from finite set to itself'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''total function from finite set to itself'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "alg/perm(v) is a permutation iff v contains each of 0,...,n-1 exactly once."
     :program "(define arr (list 3 1 0 2))\n(define p (alg/perm arr))\n(equal? (sort (map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply p i)) (list 0 1 2 3)) <)\n        (list 0 1 2 3))"
     :invariant "σ ∈ S_n ⇔ σ is a bijection {0,...,n-1} → {0,...,n-1}"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry). Also ch-advanced-02 (Combinatorics & Counting) for counting.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm — see :summary."
     :composition "(define p (alg/perm (list 2 0 1 3)))\n(define pi (alg/perm-inverse p))\n(map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply pi (alg/perm-apply p i))) (list 0 1 2 3))"
     :emergent "bijection"
     :meta "The emergent bijection belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. perm + perm-inverse = round-trip identity; the same shape as encode/decode pairs.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the bijection pattern."
     :cs "The emergent bijection is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm->cycles"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm->cycles perm) -> list-of-cycles"
  :summary "Convert a permutation to its disjoint-cycle decomposition, omitting fixed points."
  :explanation "Every permutation can be written uniquely as a product of disjoint cycles. This verb decomposes a permutation (represented as a list or vector where index i maps to element i) into that canonical cycle form. Fixed points (elements that map to themselves) are omitted from the output. The cycle structure reveals the orbit structure of the permutation and is essential for computing order, parity, and conjugacy classes."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(alg/perm->cycles '(1 2 0))  ;; maps 0→1, 1→2, 2→0\n;; Result: ((0 1 2))" :note "Single 3-cycle: elements 0,1,2 form a closed loop")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((p '(1 0 2 3)))  ;; maps 0↔1, 2→2, 3→3\n  (alg/perm->cycles p))\n;; Result: ((0 1))" :note "Transposition (0 1); fixed points 2,3 are omitted")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((cyc1 '(0 1 2))\n       (cyc2 '(3 4))\n       (p (alg/cycles->perm cyc1 cyc2 5)))\n  (equal? (alg/perm->cycles p) (list cyc1 cyc2)))\n;; Result: #t" :note "Round-trip: cycles→perm→cycles preserves structure")
  )
  :caveats ("Fixed points (self-maps) are omitted from the result." "The permutation is assumed to be a valid permutation of 0…n−1 (no validation)." "Cycle order in the output is deterministic (by first element visited) but not sorted." "Out-of-range or invalid permutations may produce undefined behavior.")
  :drawbacks ("For very large permutations, cycle decomposition is O(n) but may be memory-intensive." "If you only need parity or order, use alg/perm-parity or alg/perm-order directly (may be cheaper).")
  :usecases ("Analyzing the structure of a permutation group element." "Computing conjugacy classes (permutations with the same cycle type are conjugate)." "Determining the order of a permutation (LCM of cycle lengths)." "Debugging or visualizing permutation behavior in group problems.")
  :related ("alg/cycles->perm" "alg/perm-order" "alg/perm-parity" "alg/perm-apply" "alg/symmetric")
  :learn (:concept "Cycle notation is the standard way to represent permutations; understanding cycle structure is foundational to group theory." :prerequisites ("alg/perm-apply (how permutations act on elements)") :progression "Learn alg/perm-order and alg/perm-parity next; then move to alg/conjugacy-classes and alg/symmetric for group-level analysis.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A permutation stored as an array is opaque; the audit wants the cycle decomposition so orbit lengths and parity are visible."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3)))\n(alg/perm->cycles p)"
     :explanation "Cycles: (0 1 2)(3 4); operator reads two orbits of length 3 and 2."
     :meta "cycles->perm is the inverse direction; perm->cycles is the decomposition. Together they form a round-trip pair — a common notation-independence pattern.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'canonical decomposition of a mapping'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3)))")
       (:domain "graph strongly-connected components" :code "(graph/scc adj)")
       (:domain "cycle structure of a permutation" :code "σ = ∏ c_i"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm->cycles in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''canonical decomposition of a mapping'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''canonical decomposition of a mapping'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm->cycles."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Every permutation decomposes uniquely (up to order and cycle rotation) into disjoint cycles."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 2 0 1 4 3)))\n(define cs (alg/perm->cycles p))\n(define round-trip (alg/cycles->perm 5 cs))\n(equal? (map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply p i)) (list 0 1 2 3 4))\n        (map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply round-trip i)) (list 0 1 2 3 4)))"
     :invariant "∀ σ. σ = c_1 · c_2 · … · c_k with disjoint c_i, unique up to reordering"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm->cycles — see :summary."
     :composition "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 3 0 5 4)))\n(define cs (alg/perm->cycles p))\n(list cs (apply lcm (map length cs)))"
     :emergent "order-formula"
     :meta "The emergent order-formula belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. LCM of cycle lengths = order; the same shape as computing a system period from component periods.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the order-formula pattern."
     :cs "The emergent order-formula is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm-apply"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-apply perm i) -> number-or-nan"
  :summary "Apply a permutation to an element: return π(i), the image of i under π."
  :explanation "A permutation π is a function that rearranges elements. Given a permutation (represented as a list/vector where index j holds the image of j) and an element i, this verb returns π(i). If i is out of range, the result is 'nan. This is the fundamental operation: permutation composition, order, and cycle detection all rely on repeated application."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(alg/perm-apply '(2 0 1) 0)\n;; Result: 2" :note "Permutation [2,0,1] maps 0 to 2")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((p '(1 2 0 3)))\n  (list (alg/perm-apply p 0)\n        (alg/perm-apply p 1)\n        (alg/perm-apply p 2)\n        (alg/perm-apply p 3)))\n;; Result: (1 2 0 3)" :note "Applying p to each index recovers the permutation array")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((p '(1 0 2)))\n  (let ((p2 (alg/perm-apply p)))\n    (let loop ((i 0) (orbit (list 0)))\n      (if (= i 3)\n        orbit\n        (loop (+ i 1)\n              (if (= (alg/perm-apply p i) 0)\n                (cons i orbit)\n                orbit))))))\n;; Result: (2 0)" :note "Find elements in orbit of 0: {0, 1, 2}")
  )
  :caveats ("Out-of-range indices return 'nan (not an error)." "No validation: assumes perm is a valid permutation array." "Application is O(1) per call but repeated calls are needed for orbit/cycle computation.")
  :drawbacks ("For large orbits, manually iterating via alg/perm-apply is slow; use alg/perm->cycles instead." "Does not compose permutations; use alg/perm-compose for that.")
  :usecases ("Testing a single element's image under a permutation." "Building manual orbit traces (usually replaced by alg/perm->cycles)." "Verifying or debugging permutation definitions." "Computing powers of a permutation via repeated application (though alg/perm-pow is direct).")
  :related ("alg/perm-compose" "alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-inverse" "alg/perm-pow")
  :learn (:concept "Permutation application is the atomic action; all permutation analysis builds on it." :prerequisites () :progression "Next learn alg/perm-compose to chain applications, then alg/perm->cycles to understand global structure.")
  :row-2-audit (
