(verb
  :name "alg/perm-order"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-order perm) -> number"
  :summary "The order of a permutation: the smallest positive integer k such that p^k equals the identity."
  :explanation "The order of a permutation is determined by its cycle structure: it is the least common multiple of the lengths of all disjoint cycles. For example, a 3-cycle has order 3, a product of a 2-cycle and a 5-cycle has order 10 (lcm(2,5)). Order tells you how many times you must compose a permutation with itself to return to the identity. This is a fundamental invariant in group theory."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(alg/perm-order '(1 2 0))\n;; Single 3-cycle\n;; Result: 3" :note "Composing a 3-cycle with itself 3 times gives identity")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((p '(1 0 3 2)))  ;; Two 2-cycles: (0 1) and (2 3)\n  (alg/perm-order p))\n;; Result: 2" :note "LCM(2, 2) = 2; squaring any permutation composed of 2-cycles yields identity")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((p1 '(1 2 0))\n       (p2 '(3 4 5 6))\n       (prod (alg/perm-compose p1 p2))\n       (order-prod (alg/perm-order prod)))\n  order-prod)\n;; Result: 12" :note "Order of product: LCM(3, 4) = 12 (a 3-cycle and 4-cycle on disjoint elements)")
  )
  :caveats ("Order is always a positive integer ≥ 1." "The identity has order 1." "Order depends only on cycle type, not on which elements are in the cycles." "For disjoint cycles, order is the LCM of individual cycle lengths.")
  :drawbacks ("Computing order requires cycle decomposition, which is O(n)." "If you only need to test if order divides some k, compute order once and cache.")
  :usecases ("Analyzing the structure of permutation groups (every element has a finite order)." "Testing Lagrange's theorem (order of each element divides the group order)." "Verifying group axioms and properties." "Computing the exponent of a group (LCM of all element orders).")
  :related ("alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-pow" "alg/element-order" "alg/order" "alg/symmetric")
  :learn (:concept "Order is a fundamental invariant that connects the structure of a permutation (its cycles) to its behavior (repeated composition)." :prerequisites ("alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-compose") :progression "Learn alg/element-order for general group elements; then study Lagrange's theorem and group structure.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A repeated shuffle needs to know how many applications return to the identity, so the caller can bound the iteration."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3)))\n(alg/perm-order p)"
     :explanation "Cycles (0 1 2)(3 4) have LCM 6; operator sees 6."
     :meta "alg/element-order needs a group object; alg/perm-order works on the permutation directly. Same answer, different input contract.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'least period of an iterated map'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3)))")
       (:domain "animation loop length" :code "(animation/period clip)")
       (:domain "LCM of cycle lengths" :code "ord(σ) = lcm(|c_i|)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm-order in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''least period of an iterated map'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''least period of an iterated map'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm-order."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "ord(σ) = LCM of its disjoint cycle lengths."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3)))\n(define cs (alg/perm->cycles p))\n(= (alg/perm-order p) (apply lcm (map length cs)))"
     :invariant "ord(σ) = lcm({|c_i| : c_i ∈ cycles(σ)})"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm-order — see :summary."
     :composition "(define perms (list (alg/perm (list 1 0)) (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)) (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 4 3))))\n(map alg/perm-order perms)"
     :emergent "period"
     :meta "The emergent period belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Iteration period is a universal invariant — same shape as a clock cycle or an oscillator period.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the period pattern."
     :cs "The emergent period is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm-parity"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-parity perm) -> symbol"
  :summary "Determine the parity of a permutation: return 'even or 'odd based on the number of transpositions in its decomposition."
  :explanation "Every permutation can be written as a product of transpositions (2-cycles). While this decomposition is not unique, the parity (whether the number of transpositions is even or odd) is always the same. A permutation is even if it can be written as an even number of transpositions, and odd otherwise. Parity is determined by the cycle structure: a k-cycle is even iff k is odd. The set of all even permutations forms the alternating group A_n, a crucial structure in group theory."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(alg/perm-parity '(1 2 0))\n;; Single 3-cycle (odd number of transpositions)\n;; Result: 'even" :note "A 3-cycle is even (equals 2 transpositions)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(alg/perm-parity '(1 0 2 3))  ;; Swap 0 and 1\n;; Single 2-cycle (odd number of transpositions)\n;; Result: 'odd" :note "A transposition is odd")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let* ((p1 '(1 0))\n       (p2 '(2 1 0))\n       (prod (alg/perm-compose p1 p2)))\n  (let ((par1 (alg/perm-parity p1))\n        (par2 (alg/perm-parity p2))\n        (par-prod (alg/perm-parity prod)))\n    (list par1 par2 par-prod)))\n;; Result: ('odd 'even 'odd)" :note "Odd · Even = Odd; parity composition follows the rule (add mod 2)")
  )
  :caveats ("Parity is well-defined: every permutation is either even or odd, never both." "Parity composition rule: even·even=even, odd·odd=even, even·odd=odd." "The identity is even (it is a product of zero transpositions)." "The alternating group A_n is exactly the set of all even permutations of S_n.")
  :drawbacks ("Computing parity requires cycle decomposition (O(n))." "If you only need the sign (±1), use alg/perm-sign instead (mathematically equivalent but returns a number).")
  :usecases ("Classifying permutations into the alternating group (even) or its coset (odd)." "Computing the sign of a permutation for determinants and oriented volumes." "Analyzing group structure (the alternating group is a normal subgroup of index 2)." "Verifying properties of symmetric groups.")
  :related ("alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-sign" "alg/perm-compose" "alg/symmetric" "alg/is-normal?")
  :learn (:concept "Parity is an invariant that splits permutations into two classes; it is preserved under composition (mod 2)." :prerequisites ("alg/perm->cycles") :progression "Learn alg/perm-sign next (the numeric version); then study the alternating group A_n and its properties.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A determinant computation over permutations of matrix rows needs each permutation's parity (even/odd) as ±1 factor."
     :program "(define e (alg/perm (list 0 1 2)))\n(define t (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(list (alg/perm-parity e) (alg/perm-parity t))"
     :explanation "Identity is even, one transposition is odd; operator sees (even odd) or (0 1)."
     :meta "parity gives 'even/odd'; sign gives ±1. Same information, different encoding; use sign for arithmetic.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'parity of a discrete transformation'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define e (alg/perm (list 0 1 2)))")
       (:domain "scene state parity check" :code "(scene/mirror-count-parity stack)")
       (:domain "sign homomorphism" :code "sgn: S_n → {±1}"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm-parity in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''parity of a discrete transformation'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''parity of a discrete transformation'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm-parity."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Parity is a group homomorphism from S_n to Z/2Z with kernel A_n."
     :program "(define S3 (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define Z2 (alg/zn 2))\n(define parity (lambda (p) (if (even? (alg/perm-parity p)) 0 1)))\n(alg/is-homomorphism? S3 Z2 parity)"
     :invariant "parity: S_n → Z/2Z, parity(στ) = parity(σ) + parity(τ) mod 2"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm-parity — see :summary."
     :composition "(define S4 (alg/symmetric 4))\n(define A4 (filter (lambda (p) (even? (alg/perm-parity p))) (alg/op S4)))\n(length A4)"
     :emergent "alternating-subgroup"
     :meta "The emergent alternating-subgroup belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Same family as A_n from parity — the classical kernel-of-sign example. See book-of-code ch-02.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the alternating-subgroup pattern."
     :cs "The emergent alternating-subgroup is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm-pow"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-pow perm k) -> perm"
  :summary "Raises a permutation to the k-th power (k may be negative)."
  :explanation "A permutation composed with itself repeatedly. The k-th power of a permutation p is p∘p∘...∘p (k times). For k=0, returns the identity. For k<0, computes the inverse and raises that to |k|. This is a fundamental operation in group theory: every permutation has finite order, so pᵏ cycles through a finite set of distinct powers before returning to identity."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(alg/perm-pow p 2)" :note "Composing p with itself twice; (0→1→2→0)² = (0→2→1→0).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define order (alg/perm-order p))\n(alg/perm-pow p order)" :note "Raising p to its own order returns identity; any perm of order n satisfies pⁿ=e.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define g (alg/perm (list 1 0 2 3)))\n(define g-inv (alg/perm-pow g -1))\n(alg/perm-compose g g-inv)" :note "Computing p⁻¹ via perm-pow with k=-1, then verifying g·g⁻¹=identity by composition.")
  )
  :caveats ("k=0 returns identity, not perm itself." "Negative k requires the permutation to be invertible (always true for permutations)." "Large |k| on large permutations may exhaust iteration budget.")
  :drawbacks ("Repeated composition can be slow for large k; consider cycle structure if many powers needed." "No memoization across repeated calls; compute once and store if used multiple times.")
  :usecases ("Computing centralizers and conjugacy classes in symmetric groups." "Determining element order and subgroup membership." "Analyzing periodic symmetries in dihedral and cyclic groups.")
  :related ("alg/perm" "alg/perm-order" "alg/perm-compose" "alg/perm-inverse" "alg/perm-conjugate" "alg/element-order")
  :learn (:concept "Group exponentiation—repeated composition under the group operation." :prerequisites ("alg/perm" "alg/perm-compose") :progression "Next learn alg/perm-order and alg/element-order to understand the periodicity that perm-pow respects.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "Applying a shuffle k times must be efficient — repeated composition is O(k) but the operator wants a direct call."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(alg/perm-pow p 5)"
     :explanation "p^5 = p^(5 mod 3) = p^2 (since ord(p)=3); operator sees (2 0 1)."
     :meta "perm-compose is one step; perm-pow does k steps and can exploit ord(σ) for constant-time output. Naive repetition would be linear in k.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'exponentiation of an iterated map'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))")
       (:domain "animation frame at time k" :code "(animation/frame-at clip k)")
       (:domain "group exponentiation" :code "σ^k"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm-pow in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''exponentiation of an iterated map'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''exponentiation of an iterated map'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm-pow."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "σ^k = σ^(k mod ord(σ))."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define order (alg/perm-order p))\n(equal? (map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply (alg/perm-pow p 7) i)) (list 0 1 2))\n        (map (lambda (i) (alg/perm-apply (alg/perm-pow p (modulo 7 order)) i)) (list 0 1 2)))"
     :invariant "∀ k ∈ Z. σ^k = σ^(k mod ord(σ))"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm-pow — see :summary."
     :composition "(define p (alg/perm (list 2 0 1 3)))\n(define orbit (map (lambda (k) (alg/perm-pow p k)) (list 0 1 2 3 4)))\norbit"
     :emergent "cyclic-orbit"
     :meta "The emergent cyclic-orbit belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Iterated powers of one element = the cyclic subgroup ⟨σ⟩.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the cyclic-orbit pattern."
     :cs "The emergent cyclic-orbit is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm-sign"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-sign perm) -> {1, -1}"
  :summary "Returns +1 if the permutation is even, −1 if odd."
  :explanation "Every permutation can be decomposed into transpositions (swaps). A permutation is even if it requires an even number of transpositions; odd if an odd number. The sign is a group homomorphism from Sₙ to {±1}, and determines the permutation's membership in the alternating group Aₙ (the even permutations). Geometrically, sign encodes whether a permutation preserves or reverses orientation."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define identity (alg/perm (list 0 1 2)))\n(alg/perm-sign identity)" :note "Identity permutation is even (zero transpositions); returns +1.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define swap (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(alg/perm-sign swap)" :note "A single transposition is odd; returns −1.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define cyc3 (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define sq (alg/perm-compose cyc3 cyc3))\n(alg/perm-sign sq)" :note "A 3-cycle squared yields an even permutation; verify sign is +1.")
  )
  :caveats ("Sign is only defined for permutations; does not apply to general group elements." "The sign is invariant under conjugation; signum(g·p·g⁻¹) = signum(p).")
  :drawbacks ("Requires cycle decomposition, which is O(n) on domain size n." "Only two possible outputs; limited information beyond parity.")
  :usecases ("Checking membership in alternating group Aₙ." "Computing the determinant of a permutation matrix." "Determining orientation-preserving vs. reversing symmetries.")
  :related ("alg/perm" "alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-order" "alg/perm-parity" "alg/symmetric")
  :learn (:concept "Permutation parity as a homomorphism; orientation in group actions." :prerequisites ("alg/perm" "alg/perm->cycles") :progression "Learn alg/perm-parity for a related (but distinct) measure; explore alternating groups via alg/symmetric.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A matrix-determinant sum-over-permutations needs the ±1 factor for each permutation; a boolean parity is not directly usable in arithmetic."
     :program "(define e (alg/perm (list 0 1 2)))\n(define t (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(list (alg/perm-sign e) (alg/perm-sign t))"
     :explanation "Sign is +1 for identity, -1 for a single transposition; operator sees (1 -1)."
     :meta "parity gives even/odd as a semantic tag; sign gives ±1 as a number the caller can multiply directly. Determinant computations want the number.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: perm; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'signed indicator of a discrete transformation'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "alg native" :code "(define e (alg/perm (list 0 1 2)))")
       (:domain "signed area of a triangle" :code "(geom/signed-area a b c)")
       (:domain "sign character" :code "sgn(σ) = (-1)^{parity(σ)}"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is alg/perm-sign in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''signed indicator of a discrete transformation'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''signed indicator of a discrete transformation'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for alg/perm-sign."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "sgn is a group homomorphism S_n → {±1}, ×."
     :program "(define a (alg/perm (list 1 2 0)))\n(define b (alg/perm (list 2 1 0)))\n(= (alg/perm-sign (alg/perm-compose a b))\n   (* (alg/perm-sign a) (alg/perm-sign b)))"
     :invariant "∀ σ τ. sgn(σ ∘ τ) = sgn(σ)·sgn(τ)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (Groups & Symmetry). Also ch-advanced-12 (Linear Algebra Deep) for the determinant application.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the perm category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "alg/perm-sign — see :summary."
     :composition "(define S3 (alg/symmetric 3))\n(define signs (map alg/perm-sign (alg/op S3)))\nsigns"
     :emergent "sign-character"
     :meta "The emergent sign-character belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Sign is the simplest non-trivial character of S_n; character theory generalizes it. See book-of-ml ch-03 for matrix-side applications.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the perm operations close into the sign-character pattern."
     :cs "The emergent sign-character is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "alg/perm-support"
  :library "alg"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(alg/perm-support perm) -> list"
  :summary "Returns the list of points that the permutation moves (non-fixed points)."
  :explanation "The support of a permutation is the set of elements that are not fixed (i.e., p(x) ≠ x). A permutation can be decomposed into disjoint cycles; the support is the union of all cycle members. The complement of the support is the set of fixed points. Support is useful for understanding the structure of a permutation: smaller support means fewer elements are affected, and two permutations with disjoint supports commute."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(alg/perm-support p)" :note "Swaps 0 and 1, fixes 2; support is (0 1).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define p (alg/perm (list 1 2 0 3 4)))\n(alg/perm-support p)" :note "3-cycle on {0,1,2}, fixes {3,4}; support is (0 1 2).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define g (alg/perm (list 1 0 2)))\n(define h (alg/perm (list 0 1 3 2)))\n(equal? (alg/perm-support g) (alg/perm-support h))" :note "g and h have disjoint supports (g moves {0,1}, h moves {2,3}); they commute.")
  )
  :caveats ("Support is a list (not a set); order is determined by iteration." "Empty support means the identity permutation." "Support size ≤ domain size; equality only for regular permutations (all cycles of same length).")
  :drawbacks ("Minimal information beyond the moved points; does not reveal cycle structure." "For large domain, even reading the full support can be expensive.")
  :usecases ("Checking if two permutations commute (disjoint supports → commuting)." "Finding the minimal domain size for a permutation." "Analyzing sparsity: permutations with small support are cheaper to compose.")
  :related ("alg/perm" "alg/perm->cycles" "alg/perm-order" "alg/perm-compose")
  :learn (:concept "Support: the active part of a permutation; disjoint supports commute." :prerequisites ("alg/perm" "alg/perm->cycles") :progression "Learn alg/perm->cycles to decompose the support into its cycle structure; understand commutativity via disjoint supports.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "For a large-degree permutation that touches few elements, the operator wants the support (moved-elements) list rather than the full array, for compact logging."
     :program "(define p (alg/perm (list 0 2 1 3 4 5)))\n(alg/perm-support p)"
